# Wellbeing Log — Example
# This is an example file. Copy to memory/wellbeing-log.md and fill in your details.
# CONSTITUTION §8: The live file is gitignored. Only this .example is committed.
# Populated by wellness-companion.md and 14_wellness-checkin.md (with scholar consent).
# This file is private. Never share without explicit consent.

---

## Log Entries

> One entry per wellbeing check-in. Appended by wellness-companion.md.

### YYYY-MM-DD
date: "YYYY-MM-DD"
level: 1
# WELLBEING_STANDARD.md levels:
# 1 — Mild stress / low motivation
# 2 — Sustained stress / sleep disruption / isolation
# 3 — Exhaustion / feeling unable to continue
# 4 — Crisis signal (self-harm / immediate danger)

score: 3
# Scholar's self-rated score: 1 (really struggling) to 5 (doing well)

signal: ""
# Brief description of what the scholar described
# Example: "Feeling behind on experiments; hasn't spoken to anyone outside PhD this week"

response_given: ""
# Brief description of the support offered
# Example: "Level 1 — acknowledged, normalised, offered small win or rest day choice"

escalation: false
# true if crisis escalation message was delivered (Level 4)

kaizen_escalation: false
# true if scholar was routed to kaizen-wellbeing-reva for ongoing support

follow_up_needed: false
# true if a follow-up check-in was agreed for a specific date

follow_up_date: null
# YYYY-MM-DD or null

---

## Pattern Notes

> Manually updated by scholar or agent when patterns are noticed over multiple entries.

patterns: []
# Example:
# - "Low wellbeing scores consistently on Mondays — schedule lighter work on Mondays"
# - "Stress spikes before DRPC reviews — book wellness session 2 weeks before each review"
# - "Isolation increases when thesis writing is the focus — schedule peer check-ins during thesis phase"

---

## Self-Care Actions Tried

> Track what has helped, to build a personal self-care toolkit.

| Date | Category | Action | Helped? |
|---|---|---|---|
| YYYY-MM-DD | physical / mental / social / research-identity / boundary | [description] | yes / somewhat / no |
